Aurora: a different engine, and its endpoints.

Aurora isn't a managed open-source MySQL or PostgreSQL. It's AWS's own engine that speaks the MySQL and PostgreSQL wire protocols on the front, but reimplements the storage and replication layer underneath. That rebuild is where its numbers come from: about five times the throughput of R-D-S MySQL, and three times that of R-D-S PostgreSQL, at the same instance type. The mechanism is the shared cluster volume. In a traditional database, compute and storage live together: each instance owns its data files on its own disk, and replication means streaming write events to other instances to re-execute. Aurora separates the two. The primary and its replicas share one distributed, log-structured cluster volume. That volume keeps six copies of every piece of data across three availability zones, two per zone, and writes acknowledge on a four-of-six quorum. The replicas read the same volume, so replication lag is tiny and adding a replica adds no storage.

An Aurora cluster exposes several endpoints, each routing differently. The cluster, or writer, endpoint routes to the current primary, for writes. The reader endpoint is load-balanced across all the replicas, for reads. A custom endpoint routes to a subset of instances you define, for example larger instances dedicated to reports. And an instance endpoint routes to one specific instance, for debugging. If the primary fails and a replica is promoted, both the writer and reader endpoints update automatically, so the application never has to know which instance is currently the writer, and the reader endpoint is a D-N-S-level read load balancer you don't have to manage.
